  "doc_id": "37458",
  "text": "Diabetic nephropathy is the most common cause of end-stage renal failure in the Western world and one which contributes to the excess morbidity and mortality of patients with type 1 diabetes (9). Genetic factors are thought to contribute to the pathogenesis of nephropathy, as demonstrated by familial clustering of nephropathy [CITATION_1] . Earlier studies from our group have evaluated a series of candidate genes including the angiotensin converting enzyme, angiotensinogen [CITATION_2] and the angiotensin II type 1 receptor [CITATION_3] .",
